The schematic illustration of a tentative mechanism for the template-directed synthesis of the Ag modified Fe2O3 nanospheres is shown in Fig. 1. Initially, we synthesize Ag@C templates by hydrothermal method (A → B). Then, Ag@C templates are coated with FeOOH by stirring at room temperature (B → C). In the course of stirring, CH3COO− hydrolysis to produce OH−, then, Fe2+ react with OH− and O2, and ultimately form FeOOH (CH3COO−+H2O→CH3COOH+OH−,4Fe2++8OH−+O2→4FeOOH+2H2O\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{\rm{CH}}}_{3}{{\rm{COO}}}^{-}+{{\rm{H}}}_{2}{\rm{O}}\to {{\rm{CH}}}_{3}{\rm{COOH}}+{{\rm{OH}}}^{-},4{{\rm{Fe}}}^{2+}+8{{\rm{OH}}}^{-}+{{\rm{O}}}_{2}\to 4{\rm{FeOOH}}+2{{\rm{H}}}_{2}{\rm{O}}$$\end{document}).Next, during the calcinations at air (C → D), with the disappearance of carbon layer, Ag core breaks and diffuses, in the meantime, FeOOH converts to Fe2O3. Eventually, Ag-Fe2O3 hollow spheres are fabricated. The formation of Fe2O3 hollow structure decorated with Ag nanoparticles can be related with the removal of carbon template and surface diffusion processes. During the annealing, along with the disappearance of the carbon layer, Ag core begin to melt and shrink, leading to the presence of lots of Ag nanoparticle residues form inside the shell. The diffusion of the melted Ag nanoparticles takes place at the same time, which results in the formation of Fe2O3 hollow spheres decorated with much smaller Ag nanoparticles.Figure 1
Schematic illustration of a tentative mechanism for the template-directed synthesis of the Ag decorated Fe2O3 nanospheres.

The electrochemical properties of Ag-Fe2O3 electrode for LIBs are systematically measured by using a lithium foil electrode as reference electrode in the coin-cell batteries. The cyclic voltammetry (CV) analysis of Ag-Fe2O3 electrode collect at a scan rate of 0.1 mV s−1 between 0.01 and 3.0 V is illustrated in Fig. 5(a). The CV curves of the sample are similar to the previously reported results13, 39, 40. Plenty of differences between the first cycle and consecutive cycles are noticed. At the first cycle, there are two peaks appear in the cathodic sweep. The strong reduction peak observed at 0.67 V corresponds to the reduction of Fe (III) to Fe (0) and the formation of solid-electrolyte interface (SEI), while a broad peak locate at 0.87 V can be ascribed to Li ions insertion into Fe2O3 without structural change as follows:Fe2O3+xLi++xe−→LixFe2O3\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
